hierarchy of selectors

tag selector > class selector --< meaning --> header {css1} > .class {css}
if we have a header with class=class - it will apply the tag(header) selector {css1}

The more specific the selector --> he will have advantage against the others
header .class > .class  --- header .class is more specific and will be applied

id selector is ABOVE all

<h1 class="class1 class2 class3"> --- in css --> .h1.class1.class2.class3

if the selectors are equal the browser applies the past one in the code
header {css1}
{mores css 100 lines}
header {css2}
==> {css2} will be aplied to the header

When we wirte css --> we should start with the bigger selectors on top and 
continue downwards with the more specific ones

/* change fonts in the whole document */
html {
    /* em and rem  -- remative values for sizing */
    
    /* 1em will be equal to the font size we specify == 18px */
    /* by default the font-size of html doc is == 16px */
    font-size: 18px; 
    line-height: 1.5;
    font-family: 'Segoe UI', Tahoma, Geneva, Verdana, sans-serif;
    font-weight: normal;
    /* is equalt to */
    /* font: normal, 18px/1.5 'Segoe UI', Tahoma, Geneva, Verdana, sans-serif; */


}

margin 0 auto --- margin 0 from left and right